text.text: A Guide to Brixton

Brixton's rich history could fill a book, and we're not in the business of writing books. Broadly, though, the neighbourhood became home to post-war migrants from the West Indies, and has been a bedrock of tapestry-style multiculturalism ever since. 

Some people have no doubt been pushed out by rising housing costs in recent years, but we still saw a tight-knit community of vendors and locals who just bloody love Brixton. And you'll get to love it, too, if you have it large with us.
Best for... quality cawffee in the morn

tip.text:
This itty-bitty little ditty smack in the middle of the market serves up some of the best brew we've ever had. Seriously, their coffee is slap-up good. They'd say they owe it all to the beans - sourced from Curve Roasters as their flagship cafe - but we saw sum serious luv going into their well-crafted lattes.

A morning pit stop here should defo include a cheese-and-tomato croissant - the manager says they're the best outside of France, and while we haven't sampled all of the croissants on the planet, we can say that it was pretty freaking delicious. The rest of the menu - grilled cheese sandwiches, brownies, and other scrummy stuff - is sourced from their neighbours in the market, including Dojo pick Salon.

Best for... a short trip to Trinidad

tip.text:
Owners May and Brian want you to know that they're not Jamaican. It's easy to take a look at this tiny outpost in the market - with its colourful walls, blaring reggae, and wafting smell of jerk chicken - and feel like you stepped off a flight in Kingston. But stop thinking that immediately, because this is Trini grub, and it's a whole different game.

What remains constant between the two cultures, though, is the rum. Lots and lots of rum. Fish, Wings, & Tings has a whole menu dedicated to the stuff. Plus some serious Trini fare - jerk, catfish fritters, curry goat - to soak it all up. Be sure to try one of their three homemade hot sauces, packaged with Brian's face on them. They pack some serious fiyah.

tip.text:
This shape-shifting cafe-cum-tapas-bar-cum-cocktail-den dishes out a little taste of Spain from the morn to midnight nearly every day. The owners, Johnny and Liam, have a soft spot for Espaa, and felt that the market lacked a laid-back place where they could go out. They put their minds together and out came Seven, a casual tapas bar with serious vibes.

We're huge fans of their ever-changing cocktail list, which always features one mainstay: the refreshing af ginger beer and basil mojito. As for the tapas, they're not messing about - it's that authentic Spanish fare, like jamon serrano (cured for sixteen months) and pimiento del padron with rock salt.

Best for... Japanese street food vibes

tip.text:
This adorable little restaurant in the market looks like it was plucked straight out of the streets of Osaka - the green-hued exterior, the lantern-laden interior, the steamy kitchen with the wafting smell of delicious, carefully-prepped Japanese street food... it's the stuff of dreams.

The equally-adorable owner, Moto, moved to London 20 years ago, when there was nary a ramen restaurant to be found. She figured she had to do something about that, and so she started a stall on Brick Lane, which became a restaurant in Camberwell, which turned into Okan in Brixton Village Market and Okan Ramen down the block. Moto fancies herself 'a cook, not a chef', and so each dish has a lovingly homely feel. She specialises in Okonomiyaki at this spot - a savoury pancake with toppings such as pork, beef, and kimchi - and they're freaking delicious.

tip.text:
We can't all be glamorous - this might not be the pearly gastropub we're accustomed to finding on our corners these days, but Hootananny is a legendary local boozer. A real live music pub, expect events here most days of the week, from reggae to afrobeat nights.

A Brixton stalwart, don't be surprised to find locals shooting pool inside or watching the game on the projector. There's plenty of character about this joint, and since it's open pretty late Thurs-Sat it's definitely ideal for a drink, a smoke and a dance when the night comes.

text.text:
This one is, shall we say, a bit of a diamond in the rough. But it's still a diamond - if you look past its cruddy, uhm, everything, you'll find a community stalwart with great live music nights from Wednesday to Sunday. Its unglamorousness is just part of its charm, and it's what makes this place a local legend. 

During the day, you'll find families and white people with dreads hanging out on the sizeable terrace, greeting each other amicably. By night, you'll hear everything from reggae, to gypsy swing, to Afrobeat, with jubilant locals getting all the way loose.
Best for... an apolitical pint

tip.text:
Effra Social wasn't always the tucked away nightspot of choice for many a Brixton local and pub raver. Once upon a time, it was a Conservative social club, where Tories gathered for over 100 years to discuss right-wing politics over pints of beer and cocktails made from the tears of the poor... maybe.

But now, Effra is one of south London's most unique hotspots for late-night dancing, and whatever you think of their policies, the Tories can build a bloody good building. Part-working men's club complete with gloriously tacky decor, head down there on a weekend to find DJs spinning disco classics and guilty pleasures, or simply get lost in the many, many hidden rooms that lie within its walls. Behind the stage there's a hidden restaurant too, serving pub grub staples and decent ales.

tip.text:
You might think your love story is cute, but did it produce a top-quality neighbourhood restaurant known far and wide for its inventive food at wallet-friendly prices? No, but this one did: Margaux and Joe - who met while they were both working at Trinity in Clapham - took their penchant for fine food to the streets of Brixton when it was rapidly gentrifying in 2015. The result is Naughty Piglets, a laid back bistro with dishes that are anything but.

Here you'll find modern European small plates and an epic wine list. The menu is seasonal and constantly evolving, but if you happen to catch it, the Korean style BBQ pork belly served with a chilli miso dip is killer. And the relaxed prices mean you'll have money left over for dessert, which is always bang on - think chocolate mousse with salted peanut praline. Win-win-win.

Best for... al fresco brews

tip.text:
The Duke of Edinburgh is like Mary Poppins' handbag: unremarkable from the outside, yet somehow containing a world of wonder that you could get lost in for hours - not that we'd advocate rifling through a ladies handbag. This particular unexpected pleasure comes in the form of their massive (and yeah, we do mean massive) beer garden. It's a sprawling field with plenty of seating, rotating food pop ups, and what has become rather iconic rhino street art, where buoyant Brixtoners become imbued by that no-fucks-given festival spirit.

If the weather isn't playing your tune, you can cosy up inside where you'll find an open fire, pool tables and plenty of nooks of varying levels of romance. All that, plus DJs on the weekend, makes this a pretty alright local boozer.

text.text:
The Duke of Edinburgh is like Mary Poppins' handbag - unremarkable from the outside, but it somehow contains a world of wonder. This particular world of wonder comes in the form of their massive (and yeah, we mean massive) beer garden, but the inside isn't too bad either.

For food, The Duke welcomes a roster of rotating pop-ups. When we were there, it was White Men Can't Jerk, serving some fiery, smoky goodness. Plonk mini golf also sets up camp here in the summer - all that, plus DJs on the weekend, make this the perfect sunshiney spot.
Best for... market-fresh eating

tip.text:
As if Brixton doesn't have enough goodness in the neighbourhood, it also has one of the best restaurants in the city within its borders - Salon. This overachieving eatery wasn't content with being the favourite of local gastronome types, it also had to go and be named one of the top 40 British restaurants by the Observer. But like any overachiever, they're eager to share their accomplishments in the form of changing seasonal menus with produce sourced from the market.

The vibe: British cuisine influenced by global flavas. You can get a four-course set menu, for 36pp. Which, tbh, is a pretty sweet deal for the kind of scrummy scraps you'll be putting in your mouth. Think Jersey Royals with wild garlic and Devon blue cheese, or rhubarb with whit chocolate, sour cream, and sumac. Flavours. On. Point.

Veggies need not be scared off: the menu is always pretty plant-focused, and the adorable staff is always accommodating. Oh, and if that all wasn't enough for you, they also do brunch.

You can get a four-course set menu, including a cocktail and snacks, for 33pp. Which, tbh, is a pretty sweet deal for the kind of scrummy scraps you'll be putting in your mouth. Think Jersey Royals with wild garlic and Devon blue cheese, or rhubarb with white chocolate, sour cream, and sumac. Flavours. On. Point.
Best for... Arabian dreams

tip.text:
This is what Arabian nights are made of: part souk, part bohemian lounge, Cafe Cairo makes the perfect sanctuary from the high street drivel. A cosy den of dim lighting, snug seating and wayward musicians, this spot has all sorts rubbing their eyes in disbelief, but it's not a mirage - it's real, and we're into it. Aladdin, eat your damn heart out.

The movement (yeah, it's a movement) started 20 years ago when Cafe Cairo was merely a tent at Glastonbury. It developed a bit of a cult following, and soon found a permanent home in Brixton. Some of the old regulars still come round, alongside shiny new patrons smoking shisha side by side. What else? Banging pizzas, cabaret nights, live music, free film screenings on Sundays, and unlimited free toast, that's what else. This is one of the last true beacons of community in London - get here quick.
